{
  "texts": [
    "Vast amounts of clinical data are stored in unstructured text, such as doctor's letters.",
    "Natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) can make their information available for research and clinical routine.",
    "While supervised ML approaches rely on large amounts of manually annotated training data, recent developments in NLP showed promising results in text classification tasks using pretrained language models (PLM) and prompting (Brown et al. 2020).",
    "Prompting exploits the ability of PLMs to make correct predictions if guided through context; in combination with supervised methods, they achieve state-of-the-art results on various text classification tasks (Liu et al. 2023).",
    "Doctor's letters are typically divided into sections, such as anamnesis (patient medical history), diagnosis or medication, containing semantically related sentences."
  ]
}